<li>23 Web 2.0 platforms for content-based backlinks</li>
<li>7 wiki sites (not Wikipedia) with dofollow opportunities</li>
<li>11 document sharing sites for PDF and presentation backlinks</li>
<li>14 image sharing sites with dofollow profile links</li>
<li>13 video sharing sites with dofollow description links</li>
<li>8 Q&amp;A sites with dofollow profile and answer links</li>
<li>10 .EDU backlink opportunities</li>
<li>5 .GOV backlink opportunities</li>
<li>18 business directory sites with dofollow listings</li>
<li>10 press release sites with dofollow distribution</li>
</ul>
<h2>What Are Do-Follow Backlinks?</h2>
<p>A do-follow backlink is a hyperlink that passes link equity (also called "link juice") from one website to another. When a DA 90 website links to your page with a dofollow link, Google treats that as a vote of confidence. Your page gets a share of that authority.</p>
<p>By default, all links on the web are dofollow unless the website explicitly adds a <code>rel="nofollow"</code> attribute to the HTML. The dofollow attribute tells search engine crawlers to follow the link and pass ranking signals.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Dofollow vs nofollow backlink comparison showing how each type affects SEO" src="/images/blog/dofollow-vs-nofollow-comparison.webp" /></p>
<div class="table-wrap"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Factor</th>
<th>Dofollow Links</th>
<th>Nofollow Links</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Link equity</td>
<td>Passes PageRank</td>
<td>Does not pass PageRank</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Ranking impact</td>
<td>Direct ranking signal</td>
<td>Indirect (Google treats as "hint" since 2019)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
